column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR HIGH FLOW OXYGEN THERAPY
column13: A method of method of high flow oxygen therapy (HFOT) and carbon dioxide (CO 2 ) monitoring includes delivering high flow oxygen therapy (HFOT) via a central lumen of a nasal cannula, the nasal cannula comprising a proximal end, a distal end positioned within a pharynx region of a patient's airway, and the central lumen and a sampling lumen formed within a wall of the nasal cannula. The method also includes receiving sampled exhaled breath of the patient via the sampling lumen at a CO 2 monitor, wherein the sampling lumen is configured to sample the exhaled breath at the pharynx region through the CO2-permeable membrane and direct the sampled exhaled breath to a CO 2 monitor fluidly coupled to the sampling lumen and determining a level of CO 2 in the exhaled breath using the CO 2 monitor.

column12: CURABLE AMINE, CARBOXYLIC ACID FLUX COMPOSITION AND METHOD OF SOLDERING
column13: PURPOSE: An amine-carboxylic acid flux composite and a soldering method are provided to easily manufacture electric parts with soldered and encapsulated electric inner connections. CONSTITUTION: An amine-carboxylic acid flux composite comprises a resin component with at least two oxirane groups per molecule, a carboxylic acid, an amine flux agent, and an auxiliary curing agent as initial components. A soldering method comprises; providing a curable flux composite, a plurality of primary electric contact points, a plurality of secondary electric contact points, and solder; a step for applying the curable flux composite to a plurality of primary electric contact points and secondary electric contact points; and a step for positioning the primary electric contact points to the secondary electric contact points to be close; a step for positioning the primary electric contact points to the secondary electric contact points to be closed; a step for forming molten solder by heating the solder over reflow temperature; a step for exposing the molten solder to the primary electric contact points and the secondary electric contact points; a step for displacing the curable flux composite with the molten solder; a step for forming a plurality of electric inner connections between the primary electric contact points and the secondary electric contact points; and a step for curing the resin component and encapsulating the electric inner connections.

column12: AMINE, CARBOXYLIC ACID FLUX COMPOSITION, AND SOLDERING METHOD
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a flux composition, along with its method, which is non-hardenable and capable of facilitating reliable soldering connection, and promoting adaptivity to conventional epoxy-based underfill material.SOLUTION: The flux composition includes, as initial components, carboxylic acid and amine fluxing agent represented by formula I. The composition does not contain a compound which has two or more reactive functional groups per molecule, capable of forming an intermolecular covalent bonding by reaction under a soldering condition. Further, the amine fluxing agent does not contain two or more reactive functional groups per molecule, capable of forming an intermolecular covalent bond by reaction under a soldering condition.

column12: AMINE, CARBOXYLIC ACID FLUX COMPOSITION AND METHOD OF SOLDERING
column13: PURPOSE: An amine-carboxylic acid flux composite and a soldering method are provided to enable an unhardened soldering connection with reliability and to obtain compatibility with a normal epoxy based under fill material. CONSTITUTION: A flux composite comprises a carboxylic acid and an amine fluxing agent as initial components. A soldering method is as follows; supplying the flux composite with an electric contact, applying the flux composition to the electric contact, supplying solder, and displacing the flux composite supplied to the electric contact with molten solder. The molten solder is in physical contact with the electric contact and joined to the electric contact.

column12: Molecules comprising a calcineurin-like binding pocket and encoded data storage medium capable of graphically displaying them
column13: The present invention relates to crystallized molecules and molecular complexes which comprise the active site binding pocket or the FKBP12/FK506 binding pocket of calcineurin or close structural homologues to either binding pocket. This invention also relates to a data storage material encoded with the corresponding structure coordinates of those crystallized molecules or molecular complexes. Such data storage material is capable of displaying such molecules and molecular complexes as a graphical three-dimensional representation on a computer screen. In addition, this invention relates to methods of using the structure coordinates of those molecules or molecular complexes to solve the structure of homologous proteins. This invention also relates to methods of using the structure coordinates to screen and design compounds that bind to calcineurin or homologues thereof.

column12: Roller shade filler panel
column13: Certain embodiments of the present invention provide an apparatus for closing off an opening above, below, or between electronic equipment in a rack. The rack includes a pair of equipment rails. The electronic equipment is mounted to the equipment rails. The apparatus includes a base, a roller shade, and a handle. The roller shade is rotatably connected to the base and includes a free end extending from the base when the roller shade is rotated. The handle is connected to the free end of the roller shade. The base is removably connected to the equipment rails at a first position. The handle is removably connected to the equipment rails at a second position spaced apart from the first position such that the free end of the roller shade is extended to close off the opening in the rack.

column12: MOLECULES COMPRISING A CALCINEURIN-LIKE BINDING POCKET AND ENCODED DATA STORAGE MEDIUM CAPABLE OF GRAPHICALLY DISPLAYING THEM
column13: The present invention relates to crystallized molecules and molecular complexes which comprise the active site binding pocket or the FKBP12/FK506 binding pocket of calcineurin or close structural homologues to either binding pocket. This invention also relates to a data storage material encoded with the corresponding structure coordinates of those crystallized molecules or molecular complexes. Such data storage material is capable of displaying such molecules and molecular complexes as a graphical three-dimensional representation on a computer screen. In addition, this invention relates to methods of using the structure coordinates of those molecules or molecular complexes to solve the structure of homologous proteins. This invention also relates to methods of using the structure coordinates to screen and design compounds that bind to calcineurin or homologues thereof.

column12: Pharmacy benefits calculator
column13: A Pharmacy Benefits Calculator reads in an insured's prior pharmacy claims history and then calculates said insured's anticipated out-of-pocket costs for one or more pharmacy benefits plans that said insured is eligible to enroll in. Provision is made for an insured to modify their anticipated future pharmacy needs. Provision is also made for an insured to compare their out-of-pocket costs for different alternative drugs, said alternative drugs providing comparable therapeutic benefits. Provision also is made for an insured to substitute a lower cost generic equivalent for a brand drug, when available. Another provision is made for an insured to choose to price drugs at a retail pharmacy store or a mail order pharmacy and determine cost differences. The pricing available from said retail pharmacy store may be based on a price negotiated by an insurance company offering said pharmacy benefits plans.

column12: DURABLE ANTIREFLECTIVE FILM
column13: Antireflective films are described having a surface layer comprising a the reaction product of a polymerizable low refractive index composition comprising at least one fluorinated free-radically polymerizable material and surface modified inorganic nanoparticles. A high refractive index layer is coupled to the low refractive index layer. In one emboidiment, the high refractive index layer comprises surface modified inorganic nanoparticles dispersed in a crosslinked organic material. The antireflective film is preferably durable, exhibiting a haze of less than 1.0% after 25 wipes with steel wool using a 3.2 cm mandrel and a mass of 1000 grams.

column12: Roller shade filler panel
column13: Certain embodiments of the present invention provide an apparatus for closing off an opening above, below, or between electronic equipment in a rack. The rack includes a pair of equipment rails. The electronic equipment is mounted to the equipment rails. The apparatus includes a base, a roller shade, and a handle. The roller shade is rotatably connected to the base and includes a free end extending from the base when the roller shade is rotated. The handle is connected to the free end of the roller shade. The base is removably connected to the equipment rails at a first position. The handle is removably connected to the equipment rails at a second position spaced apart from the first position such that the free end of the roller shade is extended to close off the opening in the rack.

column12: EXPANDABLE INTERBODY SPACER
column13: Devices and methods for treating one or more damaged, diseased, or traumatized portions of the spine, including intervertebral discs, to reduce or eliminate associated back pain. In one or more embodiments, the present invention relates to an expandable interbody spacer. The expandable interbody spacer may comprise a first jointed arm comprising a plurality of links pivotally coupled end to end. The expandable interbody spacer further may comprise a second jointed arm comprising a plurality of links pivotally coupled end to end. The first jointed arm and the second jointed arm may be interconnected at a proximal end of the expandable interbody spacer. The first jointed arm and the second jointed arm may be interconnected at a distal end of the expandable interbody spacer.

column12: TUBE POSITION MONITORING SYSTEM
column13: A position monitoring system is provided that includes a tracheal tube having a distal portion with a radiopaque indicator. The tracheal tube is configured to be positioned within an airway of a patient. The position monitoring system also includes an external sensor configured to be positioned on an external surface of the patient. The external sensor includes an emitter configured to transmit energy into the patient and toward the distal portion and a detector configured to receive a reflected portion of the energy to permit identification of a position of the distal portion. The position monitoring system, in certain embodiments, further includes a video laryngoscope communicatively coupled to the external sensor. The video laryngoscope includes a display and a processor, and the processor is configured to instruct the display to present an indication of the position of the distal portion based on feedback from the detector.

column12: VERFAHREN, SYSTEME UND EINRICHTUNGEN ZUM REKONFIGURIEREN EINES COMPUTERS
column13: Es sind Verfahren, Systeme und Einrichtungen zum Rekonfigurieren eines Computers offenbart. Eine beispielhafte elektronische Vorrichtung beinhaltet mindestens einen Speicher, Anweisungen in der elektronischen Vorrichtung und eine Prozessorschaltungsanordnung zum Ausführen von Anweisungen zum Analysieren von Daten, die einer ersten Konfiguration der elektronischen Vorrichtung entsprechen, um eine mit der elektronischen Vorrichtung assoziierte Änderung zu erkennen, wobei die erste Konfiguration einem jeweiligen ersten Benutzerprofil entspricht, Ermitteln einer zweiten Konfiguration der elektronischen Vorrichtung basierend auf der erkannten Änderung und Anpassen einer Konfiguration der elektronischen Vorrichtung von der ersten Konfiguration auf die zweite Konfiguration.

column12: METHODS, SYSTEMS, AND APPARATUS TO RECONFIGURE A COMPUTER
column13: Methods, systems, and apparatus to reconfigure a computer are disclosed. column12: HUMIDIFICATION SYSTEM
column13: A humidification system can include a heater base, a chamber, and a breathing circuit. The heater base includes a heater plate positioned in a recessed region, and a heat conductive portion of the chamber is configured to contact the heater plate. The heater base includes a guard configured to control movement of the chamber into and out of the recessed region. The guard includes an anti-racking mechanism. Methods of controlling the respiratory humidification system are described, including determining whether an outlet port temperature has increased by more than a predetermined amount in a predetermined time, or setting a target dew point. column12: Humidification system
column13: The assembly 2900 comprises a heater plate (2903, fig 29C) a heating element (2930) and a heater plate set 2925 having one or more insulation layers located between the plate and element. The heater plate may be mounted on springs allowing the assembly to be depressed during installation of a humidification chamber. The assembly may comprise a back plate and a back plate set 2920 comprising at least one insulation layer located between the back plate and the opposite side of the heating element. The assembly may comprise two wires and insulation pieces 2915 to insulate the wires from the back plate. The heating element may comprise a flat filament wound around a non-conductive core.

column12: HUMIDIFICATION SYSTEM
column13: A respiratory humidification system comprising: a heater base comprising at least a chamber and a heat source, the chamber including an inlet and an outlet, the heat source configured to heat a liquid to humidify a flow of gases provided by the gases source and flowing from the inlet to the outlet of the chamber; one or more sensors positioned at or near the chamber inlet and/or outlet and configured to monitor parameters of the flow of gases when the respiratory humidification system is in a first operating mode; a hardware and/or software controller in electrical communication with the one or more sensors, the hardware and/or software controller configured to: detect one or more flow anomaly conditions (3012, 3014, 3016) using the monitored parameters when the humidification system is in the first operating mode; upon detection of the one or more flow anomaly conditions (3012, 3014, 3016), change the operating mode of the humidification system from the first operating mode (3010) to at least one second operating mode (3020) to determine a cause of the one or more flow anomaly conditions; and determine whether the flow of gases is reverse to a normal flow of gases under normal operating circumstances of the first operating mode using the monitored parameters when the humidification system operates in the at least second operating mode (3020).
